DOCUMENT();
loadMacros( "PGbasicmacros.pl",
                     "MathObjects.pl",
	             "PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl",
                     "BrockPhysicsMacros.pl",
	             "PGchoicemacros.pl",
	             "PGanswermacros.pl",
                     "PG_CAPAmacros.pl",
                     "answerHints.pl"
);

TEXT(beginproblem());

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;
$showHint = 3;

$A = random(1,2,1);
$T1C = random(1200,1250,1);
$T2C = random(30,39,1);
$T1 = ($T1C+273.15)**4;
$T2 = ($T2C+273.15)**4;
$T = $T2-$T1;
$e = sprintf("%0.2f",1);
$o = 5.67*(10**-8);
$P = ($o*$e*$A*$T)*(1/1000);

Context() -> texStrings;
BEGIN_TEXT

$PAR

<b>If you do not answer this question correctly in $showHint attempts, you can get a hint.</b>

$PAR

Radiation makes it impossible to stand close to a hot lava flow. Calculate the rate of
heat transfer by radiation from \($A\) \(\textrm{m}^2\) of \($T1C ^{\circ}\textrm{C}\) fresh lava into \($T2C ^{\circ}\textrm{C}\) surroundings, assuming lava's emissivity is \($e\).


$PAR

\{ans_rule(40)\} \(\textrm{kW}\)

$PAR

END_TEXT
BEGIN_HINT
Recall the Stefan-Boltzmann Law of Radiation requires the temperatures be converted into units of Kelvin.
END_HINT

Context() -> normalStrings;

ANS(num_cmp("$P"));



ENDDOCUMENT()